It can also be used more generally to refer to the internal ordering of any representation, such as the digits in a numeral system or the sections of a date. In its most common usage, endianness indicates the ordering of bytes within a multi-byte number. A big-endian ordering places the most significant byte first and the least significant byte last, while a little-endian ordering does the opposite. For example, consider the unsigned hexadecimal number 0x1234, which requires at least two bytes to represent.
